SIMPLE: willing
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Willing
<hw>Will"ing</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Will</er>,
<pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Free to do or to grant; having the mind inclined;
not opposed in mind; not choosing to refuse; disposed; not averse;
desirous; consenting; complying; ready.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Felix, <qex>willing</qex> to show the Jews a pleasure, left Paul
bound.</q> <rj><qau>Acts xxiv. 27.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>With wearied wings and <qex>willing</qex> feet.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[Fruit] shaken in August from the <qex>willing</qex> boughs.</q>
<rj><qau>Bryant.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Received of choice, or without reluctance; submitted
to voluntarily; chosen; desired.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>[They] are held, with his melodious harmony,⟦br⟧
In <qex>willing</qex> chains and sweet captivity.</q>
<rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Spontaneous; self-moved.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>No spouts of blood run <qex>willing</qex> from a tree.</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Willingly</ent>⟦br⟧
